📌 Day 1 – Problem Breakdown, Data Planning & Tool Design

Day 1 was spent breaking down the assignment into concrete system components instead of jumping directly into coding.

I started by analyzing the core requirement: building an agentic RAG system that can dynamically choose between multiple data sources. The key difference from a normal RAG pipeline is that the agent must decide which tool to use and when, rather than always retrieving from a single vector store.

🔹 Understanding the System Requirements

From the problem statement, I identified three mandatory capabilities:

Semantic retrieval from unstructured documents
Querying structured data (CSV/SQL)
Fetching real-time information from web search

Instead of treating these as features, I treated them as independent tools with strict input/output contracts, since the LLM will rely on tool descriptions to make decisions.

🔹 Tool-Level Design (Done on Day 1)

Before writing any code, I designed the interface of all three tools:

search_docs
Input: natural language query
Output: top-k relevant chunks + source + page
Planned using embeddings + vector store (FAISS/Chroma)
query_data
Input: structured query (SQL / natural language)
Output: table or scalar value
Decided to use pandas first (faster to iterate), with optional SQL abstraction later
web_search
Input: short query string
Output: top results with URL + snippet
Planned integration with Tavily / DuckDuckGo API

The main focus here was making outputs consistent and predictable, since inconsistent tool outputs will break the agent reasoning later.

🔹 Architecture Thinking (Important Part)

Instead of thinking “LLM → answer”, I structured the system as:

User Query → Agent Loop → Tool Selection → Tool Execution → Context Update → Final Answer

The critical part is the agent loop, which must:

Decide tool dynamically
Track previous steps
Stop after max 8 steps (hard constraint from assignment)

I sketched a rough control flow using a simple loop:

Step counter
Tool decision logic
Context accumulation
Termination condition
🔹 Data Planning (What I Decided)

I also planned the dataset early to avoid rework:

Unstructured → Annual reports / long documents
Structured → CSV with financial metrics (multi-year data)
Web → live search for recent updates

The goal is to ensure:

Queries require multi-tool reasoning, not just single retrieval
Dataset supports both numerical + textual questions
🔹 Key Decisions Taken
Not using any black-box agent frameworks (as restricted)
Keeping agent loop simple (<100 lines target)
Prioritizing tool correctness before agent logic
Planning trace logging from the beginning (for debugging + evaluation)
🔹 Challenges Identified Early
Tool selection ambiguity (LLM may choose wrong tool)
Handling multi-step reasoning without loops
Maintaining consistent output format across tools

These will be addressed in later stages during agent implementation.

🔹 Outcome of Day 1

By the end of Day 1:

Problem was fully decomposed into components
Tool interfaces were clearly defined
System architecture and flow were finalized
Dataset strategy was planned

This sets up Day 2 for actual implementation of individual tools.
